EVENT.description: Any concept describing something changing in time.

OBJECT.description: Any reference to a class of objects.

EXPERIENCEABLE OBJECT.description: Any reference to a class of experienceable objects.

ABSOLUTE TIME REFERENCES.description: A pointer to a time in the future or past defined without reference to the time of enunciation.

RELATIVE TIME REFERENCE.description: A time in the future or past defined by reference to the time of enunciation.

EVENT TENSE.description: The general position in time at which an event occurs, relative to the time of enunciation.

PAST EVENT.description: Before the real or imaginary speaker time.

JUST A MOMENT AGO.description: A few minutes/hours in the past of the speaker.

A SHORT WHILE AGO.description: A few hours/days in the past of the speaker.

SOME TIME AGO.description: Some days/weeks in the past of the speaker.

A LONG TIME AGO.description: Some months/years in the past of the speaker.

A VERY LONG TIME AGO.description: Many years in the past of the speaker.

FUTURE EVENT.description: After the real or imaginary speaker time.

SHORTLY AFTER NOW.description: A short duration after the speaker time.

ASPECT.description: The way an event is viewed in relation to the flow of time.

PERFECTIVE.description: An event that has been completed.

DEICTIC.description: A pointer relative to the real or imaginary speaker.

OBJECT DEICTIC.description: A relative pointer to an object.

Ref_2_people_including_addressee.description: A reference to the addressee and someone else but not the speaker.

Ref_3_people_including_addressee.description: A relative pointer to the addressee and two other people but not the speaker.

Ref_1_person.description: A relative pointer to someone else but not the speaker or the addressee.

Ref_2_people.description: A relative pointer to two people different from the speaker or the addressee.

Ref_3_people.description: A relative pointer to three people different from the speaker or the addressee.

Ref_many_people.description: A relative pointer to several people that do not include speaker or addresse.

DEFINITENESS.description: Whether an entity is considered definite or indefinite.

PERSONAL DEICTIC.description: Reference to a person or personified object in relation with the real or imaginary speaker.

Ref_speaker_plus_many_excluding_addresse.description: Speaker and a number of people above discrete count but not the adressee.

Ref_speaker_plus_person_excluding_addres.description: The speaker and someone else but not the addressee

Ref_speaker_plus_many_including_addresse.description: The speaker, the addressee and more people than discrete count

existing.description: Existing: expresses the existence of something

ABSTRACT PROPERTY.description: Any reference to an abstract property

experiencing in the body.description: Experiencing something in the body, as heat, cold, or pain

causality wildcard.description: Reference to something unknown that is the cause of an event

DISAPPROVE.description: Express that what has been said is untrue

OBLIQUE ROLE GOAL.description: Oblique Role Goal, as TO in I want the key TO open the door

OBLIQUE ROLE ORIGIN.description: Oblique Role Origin, as FROM in I am coming FROM the village

Ref_paucal_objects.description: Reference to a handful (paucal) number of known objects

OBLIQUE ROLE DESTINATION.description: Oblique Role Destination, as TO in giving something TO someone

EXPRESS LIKELIHOOD.description: Express likelihood, as in: it must be...

POLARITY.description: Polarity: spectrum from affirmation to negation

INCLUSIVE PREDICATE.description: Inclusive Predicate: Expresses that something belongs to a given category/class

ATTRIBUTIVE PREDICATE.description: Attributive Predicate: Expresses that something exposes a given quality

EXISTENTIAL PREDICATE.description: Existential Predicate: Expresses that something does exist.

NUMERAL PREDICATE.description: Numeral Predicate: Expresses the quantity of some object.

LOCATIVE PREDICATE.description: Locative Predicate: Expresses that something that exists is somewhere.

EQUATIVE PREDICATE.description: Equative Predicate: Expresses that something and something else are the same thing.

PROCESSIVE PREDICATE.description: Processive Predicate: An event is happening.

SPATIAL DEICTIC.description: A spatial pointer relative to the real or imaginary speaker.

INTENSIFIER.description: Intensifier: as REALLY in I REALLY need this

Ref_many_people_including_addressee.description: Reference to many people, including the addressee

OPEN CONVERSATION.description: Open Conversation: in English: you know what, guess what, so, listen...

IN FUTURE DIRECTION.description: In Future Direction, as IN in IN two months

IN PAST DIRECTION.description: In Past Direction, as AGO in two months AGO

EXPRESS BELIEF (EPISTEMIC).description: Express Belief (English SHOULD in the train SHOULD arrive at 5pm)

GIVE ADVICE (ADVISORY).description: Give Advice, as English SHOULD in you SHOULD come with me

OBLIQUE ROLE MANNER.description: Oblique Role Manner, as HOW in This is HOW you do it.

OBLIQUE ROLE MEDIUM.description: Oblique Role Medium: The medium on which an action is perfomed, as ON a notebook.

SPATIAL ON.description: Spatial location ON, as in ON the desk

OBLIQUE ROLE TRANSFORMATION.description: Oblique role transformation as INTO in shredding it INTO pieces

POSITION IN SEQUENCE.description: Position in sequnce, for example position 1 is FIRST in English.

POINTER TO X.description: Pointer to something. As in English that, which, those etc.

PRESENT X.description: here is X, this is X

POINTED BY SPEAKER.description: Pointed by the speaker, as THERE in english

mothers side.description: On the side of the mother

COMPARER.description: The object compared to a reference in a comparison

APPRECIATIVE PREDICATE.description: Appreciative Predicate: Expresses an opinion about what hae been just said

GENERIC FUTURE.description: Any time in the future of the real or imaginary speaker.

GENERIC PAST.description: Whenever in the past of the real of imaginary speaker.
